<theorem xml:id="th_substition_polar">
  <idx><h>substition</h><h>polar coordinates</h></idx>
  <title>Polar change of variables</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      The function
      <md>
        <mrow>G\colon \R^2 \amp\rightarrow \R^2 </mrow>
        <mrow> (r,\theta)\amp \mapsto (\underset{x}{\underbrace{r\cos\theta}}, \underset{y}{\underbrace{r\sin\theta}}) </mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    is a continuously differentiable transformation on any subset of the <m>r\theta</m>-plane:
    <me>
      \{(r,\theta)\colon r\gt 0, 0\leq \theta\lt 2\pi\}
    </me>.
    Given a region <m>\mathcal{R}</m> whose interior lies within this set, let <m>\mathcal{S}=G(\mathcal{R})</m> be its image under the polar transformation <m>G</m>. The Jacobian of <m>G</m> is
    <men xml:id="eq_Jacobian_polar">
      \frac{\partial(x,y)}{\partial(r,\theta)}=\det\begin{pmatrix}
        \cos\theta \amp -r\sin\theta\\ \sin\theta\amp r\cos\theta
    \end{pmatrix}=r(\cos^2\theta+\sin\theta^2)=r.
  </men>
    By <xref ref="th_substitution"/>, we have
    <mdn>
      <mrow xml:id="eq_substition_polar">  \iint\limits_\mathcal{S}f(x,y)\, dA \amp =\iint\limits_\mathcal{R}f(r\cos\theta, r\sin\theta) \, r\, dA \amp (r\gt 0\implies \abs{r}=r) </mrow>
    </mdn>.

   </statement>
</theorem>

<theorem xml:id="th_substition_cylindrical">
  <idx><h>substition</h><h>polar coordinates</h></idx>
  <title>Cylindrical change of variables</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      The function
      <md>
        <mrow>G\colon \R^3 \amp\rightarrow \R^3 </mrow>
        <mrow> (r,\theta, z)\amp \mapsto (\underset{x}{\underbrace{r\cos\theta}}, \underset{y}{\underbrace{r\sin\theta}}, z) </mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    is a continuously differentiable transformation on any region <m>\mathcal{R}</m> contained in the following subset of the <m>r\theta z</m>-plane:
    <men>
      \{(r,\theta,z)\in \R^3\colon r\gt 0, 0\leq \theta\lt 2\pi\}
    </men>.
    Given a region <m>\mathcal{R}</m> whose interior lies within this set, let <m>\mathcal{S}=G(\mathcal{R})</m> be its image under the polar transformation <m>G</m>. The Jacobian of <m>G</m> is
    <men xml:id="eq_Jacobian_cylindrical">
      \frac{\partial(x,y,z)}{\partial(r,\theta,z)}=\det\begin{pmatrix}
        \cos\theta \amp -r\sin\theta\amp 0\\ \sin\theta\amp r\cos\theta\amp 0\\ 0\amp 0\amp 1
    \end{pmatrix}=r(\cos^2\theta+\sin\theta^2)=r.
  </men>
      By <xref ref="th_substitution"/>, we have
    <mdn xml:id="eq_substitution_cylindrical">
      <mrow>  \iiint\limits_\mathcal{S}f(x,y,z)\, dV \amp =\iiint\limits_\mathcal{R}f(r\cos\theta, r\sin\theta, z) \, r\, dV \amp (r\gt 0\implies \abs{r}=r) </mrow>
    </mdn>.

   </statement>
</theorem>
